ce:section.ce:para:
The analytical capabilities of the dual-emission system (Cu2+/NCDs /EY) were evaluated using MET concentrations from 0 to 10.0 μM under optimized conditions. The sensing mechanism demonstrated a concentration-dependent dual-signal response: enhanced Cu2+/NCDs fluorescence at 403 nm accompanied by simultaneous decrease in EY emission at 536 nm (Fig. 3

                        A). Quantitative analysis revealed excellent linearity between the ratiometric fluorescence response (F403/F536) and MET concentration across the tested range (Fig. 3
                        B), following the equation F403/F536 = 0.55CMET + 0.49 with a correlation coefficient of 0.9984. The method achieved high sensitivity with a detection limit of 28.15 nM. A comprehensive comparison with previously reported methods (Table 1
                        ) demonstrates the superior analytical performance of this ratiometric approach. While certain reported techniques show comparable or lower detection limits, the current method overcomes several practical limitations discussed earlier, offering advantages in terms of simplicity, speed, and reliability for MET determination. The distinct shift in fluorescence color was validated using the International Commission on Illumination (CIE 1931) chromaticity diagram (

                           Fig. S4

                        ).

The selectivity of the dual-emission sensing system (Cu2+/NCDs /EY) was rigorously evaluated against potential interfering substances commonly present in biological samples. The interference study included various heavy metal cations, biological molecules, and frequently co-administered medications (

                           Fig. S5

                        ). The tested compounds encompassed cholesterol, glucose, urea, lactose, amino acids (proline, lysine), antidiabetic drugs (glimepiride, glipizide, sitagliptin), statins (atorvastatin, simvastatin), furosemide, and lactic acid. Under optimized conditions, each potential interferent was individually assessed alongside MET as a reference. The ratiometric fluorescence response (F403/F536) showed remarkable specificity, with significant signal enhancement observed exclusively in the presence of MET. The negligible interference from these diverse compounds demonstrates the high selectivity of the sensing platform, validating its applicability for accurate MET determination in complex plasma matrices.

The practical utility of the method was demonstrated through quantification of MET in plasma samples obtained from rats. Analysis of real plasma samples yielded excellent recovery values between 98.00–101.00 %, with precision confirmed by RSD values not exceeding 3.09 % (

                              Table S1

                           ). Method validation was accomplished by analyzing identical plasma samples using both the developed method and a reference LC/MS technique [9]. The recovery percentages obtained from both methods showed strong correlation, and no significant differences between them. The comparable performance with the standard HPLC method confirms the reliability and accuracy of our newly developed approach for MET determination in biological samples.
